sentences: Peter Naphtali Lemer (born 14 June 1942) is an English jazz musician.
He currently works with In Cahoots, Peter Lemer Trio/Quartet, Barbara Thompson's Paraphernalia, and the Peter Lemer-Billy Thompson Quartet and Duo.
In 1965, Lemer formed a trio with John Stevens and Jeff Clyne, which opened the Little Theatre Club.
In 1966, he formed the Peter Lemer Quintet, with Jon Hiseman on drums, George Khan on tenor sax, John Surman on baritone sax and Tony Reeves on bass.
This band successfully played a season at Ronnie Scott's and helped to pave the way for the British free jazz movement of the late 1960s and early 1970s, along with the Mike Taylor trio.

In 1969, Lemer worked with the Spontaneous Music Ensemble, an experimental jazz group.
In that year, he also joined Barbara Thompson.

Paraphernalia became the most frequently performing jazz-oriented group in Europe, and Lemer was keyboardist for most of the years up to the present, including ten albums recorded live or at Thompson and Hiseman's Temple Music Studios.
In 1974, Lemer joined Gilgamesh and played several gigs and some BBC sessions.
In 1974, he joined Ken Elliot's Seventh Wave, a pioneer synthesiser-based rock band, appearing on their second album, Psi-Fi.
In 1975, he joined Ginger Baker, Mr Snips, and The Gurvitz brothers in the Baker Gurvitz Army - recording Elysian Encounter .
In 1976, he joined Jan Dukes de Grey briefly to record their final album, Strange Terrain.

With them, he played on the album Cutting Both Ways (1987) and toured Europe.
He joined the band Paraphernalia in 1987 and played on the albums A Cry from the Heart (1987), Everlasting Flame (1993) and Shifting Sands.
